                  </rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18310407-233-victim1635 t18310407-233-viclabel1252"></join>. The prisoner was in my service twenty-two months, as <rs id="t18310407-233-deflabel1254" type="occupation">porter</rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18310407-233-defend1634 t18310407-233-deflabel1254"></join>, and was so on the 1st of March; many gentlemen complained of losing property - I got a search-warrant, and found on his premises a quantity of carpet, pieces of candle, and a number of duplicates of glass, which I believe to be my property; I have pieces of carpet similar to those found, and the candles are a peculiar make - I have missed candles from time to time.</p>
               <p>Cross-examined by MR. PHILLIPS. Q. What is the peculiar make? A. They are made to fit candlesticks which I have - they are not a common length; I had them made short for the use of the bed-room; they are tallow - I had not sold any carpets - I had a man named Hill in my employ; I sold him some carpet once, but I sold none while the prisoner lived with me - when I said I had not sold any carpets, I meant while the prisoner had lived with me - some of these pieces are old, and some are much worn - I know nothing of the prisoner buying any carpet of Hill - I may have sold him six or seven patterns, or there might be twenty; these may be called remnants; they are cut up I took the prisoner on the recommendation of our head porter, Hill - I believe he had lived formerly with my predecessor, for four or five years.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18310407-233-person1637">
                  EDWARD 
                  RURRIDGE
               <interp inst="t18310407-233-person1637" type="surname" value="RURRIDGE"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18310407-233-person1637" type="given" value="EDWARD"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18310407-233-person1637" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am an officer, of High-street. I went to the prisoner's lodgings on the 14th of March; he was not at home, but his wife was - I found some of these carpets on the floor, and some on a chair - the candles were in a cupboard - I was called down stairs, and when I got up again, I found his wife had removed them into another room - I took the prisoner there between five and six o'clock next morning, and told him it was on suspicion of stealing various things from his master - he said, "My wife has told me all about it; I have not taken any thing" - he did not show the least fear.</p>
